To Whom It May Concern,I have been cycling over the Longfellow bridge for many years. I was very glad to see the construction finish this past year, and the inclusion of a designated bike lane. However, the way the bike lane is constructed on the Westbound side of the bridge (headed from Boston to Cambridge) at the base of the bridge on the Cambridge side as the Land Boulevard connects back in creates for a very dangerous situation for riders. The bike lane takes a VERY dramatic "zig zag" and furthermore there is a raised curb in this section as well as standing plastic bike lane barriers.Many cyclists are afraid while navigating this zig zag in the bike lane, especially because the raised curb is so high. I have seen many cyclists on the shared "Blue Bikes" all but come to a stop trying to make this sharp turn, which creates a very dangerous situation for other cycles behind them. This is a heavily bicycled route.It is unclear why the lane was made with this "zig zag" feature. I think it would behoove everyone if it were reconstructed to be a smoother, straighter line from the already existent bike lane coming over the bridge.Sincerely,Leia Dwyer

To whom it may concern,I bicycle through Cambridge to Downtown Boston everyday via Beacon/Hampshire. Many mornings between 7:15 and 7:45, I have encountered a yellow school bus parking at the intersection of Windsor and Hampshire, on the right hand side of the street (headed southeast) right in front of Lord Hobo. This is a very narrow and busy intersection. The bus is parked right up to the corner, leaving no room for a right hand turn. Importantly, this also leaves no room for bicycles to collect at the top of the lane to wait for the light.This morning I took down the bus number, 158. I'm not sure if it's the same physical bus or driver every day but the recurrence is common and it creates a very dangerous situation for pedestrians, cars, and cyclists. Please do your best to communicate this to the right people to rectify this situation.Sincerely,Leia Dwyer

Dear Sir/Madame,I'm writing to report a bike accident that occurred on Thurs, July 19 on Broadway ST near the MIT campus.  I was riding on my bike in the direction of the Longfellow bridge. Shortly before the intersection Broadway and Anne St, I passed a construction site that was right adjacent to the bike lane (doing work, as it seemed, on the side walk). When I passed the construction site, at a relatively high speed, I hit a wooden log that was sticking out on the street from the construction site. As result, I lost balance and crashed onto the street.  I occurred bruises on my right elbow, right leg and upper back. On top of that, I have been experiencing lower back pain for more than 7 days now since the accident happened. This accident could have been prevented. First, the log that my bike hit was clearly sticking out onto the street, beyond the perimeter of the construction site.  Second, there was NO POLICEMAN on duty at the construction site when the accident occurred, even though the site appeared to be an active one. If you need to verify the course of events:  The accident should be listed in the accident log of the Cambridge Police as I had called 911 right after the accident and spoke to two members of the Cambridge Police who showed up at the construction site about 10min after the accident occurred. The construction site was overseen by a contracting company called Moriarty.  I would like to ask you to address this issue with the construction contractor and police department in charge of the construction work on that day so that, in the future, similar needless accidents can be avoided on the streets of Cambridge.Sincerely, Stefan

Three scooters are fine in car centric areas like California or Texas where they drive on the unused sidewalks. Here sidewalks and bicycle lanes are already busy, having motor vehicles like these and segways makes life much worse for pedestrians and bicyclists

Hi there. Categorizing this as a bike lane obstruction, but this is also an MBTA issue, and I hope the city can coordinate with them on this.The 66 bus route's northbound/outbound stop for Harvard Square is at the Johnston Gate bus shelter. However, I've noticed pretty frequently (in the evening rush hour, at least) that the 66 route coming from JFK will angle across the right travel lane and the northbound bike lane on Mass Ave to let passengers off about 300 feet south of the Johnston Gate stop. I assume this is because they are stopped in traffic due to the signal opposite Church St. Although stopping well south of Johnston Gate might be convenient for bus riders, this informal stop can lead to bikers suddenly mixing with alighting pedestrians in the bike lane (if the bus hasn't totally blocked the bike lane), and feels uncomfortable on a bike because of the squeeze of the bus. It also prevents cyclists from taking advantage of the red light up ahead so they can make a legal left turn across Mass Ave onto Church St. Could the city work with the MBTA to get the 66 to drop passengers at Johnston Gate only? Or at worst, could this stop be formally marked and signed so bikers know to expect this kind of interaction here?  Thanks a lot for your help.

Not truly a bicycle lane obstruction, but close enough.  The motor vehicle pictured was parked in a clearly marked "No Stopping Anytime" Zone and over a hashed white buffer zone.  Parking in this location creates a severe reduction in visibility, such that cyclists are in extreme danger of being right hooked by vehicles attempting to turn from Ames Street onto Ames Place.  In fact, I was almost right hooked this morning myself.Please consider installing a couple of bollards or other "more than paint" devices to indicate this is a No Parking Zone.  Leaving parked vehicles here creates an extreme risk of severe injury, and perhaps more importantly, there is *nothing* that cyclists can do to protect themselves in this situation while using the protected bicycle lane as designed.If Cambridge is serious about VisionZero, this seems like a great place to spend a very small amount of money to get a big increase in safety.And yes, I did call CPD to report this vehicle. issue_description: Private passenger vehicle parked completely obstructing the protected bicycle lane, leaving no safe space for cyclists to proceed.  I stopped to take the attached picture, and was about to call CPD when I saw a CPD officer across the street at a construction site.  I called over to him and pointed out the vehicle and he said "I'll take care of it."  I walked by a few minutes later and indeed it did appear that he was ticketing the vehicle.However, when a vehicle is obstructing a protected bike lane like this we really need more aggressive action.  Either a police officer needs to be directing cyclists around the effectively closed road, or in egregious cases like this, the vehicle should simply be towed.  It's pretty obvious that this is not a legal parking spot, and if this vehicle were blocking the "car lane" it'd likely be immediately towed as a hazard.A simple fix might be to just put an orange cone or two down in the buffer near the beginning and end (to catch someone trying to reverse/parallel park) of this lane, making it even more obvious that this is not a space for motor vehicles to park.

At approximately 9:30am this morning I encountered Cambridge Fire's Engine 5 parked with it's lights and engine off, obstructing the bike lane on Hampshire St near Union St.  I saw three firefighters congregated outside of a house on Union St, so I walked over and asked them to please turn on the lights, to make it more obvious that there's an emergency and that other road users should give adequate space.  They kind of gave me a bit of an attitude, it's unclear if that was because there was an active emergency (though they didn't seem in a rush, and if it was an emergency shouldn't the lights already be on?) or if they just think they can ignore road safety because they're driving a fire truck.Please work with all Cambridge emergency services (and tow truck operators!) to establish a clear, concise guideline about proper use of emergency lights when obstructing any part of the road for an emergency call.  The key is to alert road users to potential unpredictability, the last thing any road user wants to do is hit an emergency responder rushing to get lifesaving equipment out of the truck!

On 5/9/18 at 5:30pm, I was traveling in the marked bike lane on Eliot Street. Parked in the bike lane was a Bentley University bus (license plate 39132). I had to decide whether to go into the car lane or stop and lift my bike onto the sidewalk to get around the bus. The bus was parked, with its flashers on, and the bus driver was standing on the sidewalk before boarding the bus. As I passed the bus, I kindly informed him that he was parked in the bike lane. He snarkily replied "no, it's not a bike lane, we stop here too, good day" and then shut the door in my face before driving off. I understand that there is an MBTA bus stop located here, but this is a private bus that was not stopping to pick up passengers but actually completely stopped (for who knows how long). It's one thing for buses to pull over at the stop, but another entirely to use it as a private parking space, especially for private buses. This parking behavior should not be permitted as it endangers our bicyclists. Furthermore, this bus driver should be educated as to the rights of bicyclists on the road of Cambridge. Could a City official reach out to the Bentley shuttle manager at 781-891-2685 to educate them?

I'd like to formally request that the "slip lane" from Hampshire St to Antrim St be closed to motor vehicle (or all) traffic.  While biking down Hampshire St today I was nearly hit today by a motorist who did not signal before attempting to make a last second turn, through me.  After somehow not falling over or as far as I can tell, hitting his car, I came to a stop by the traffic island and directed the motorist to stop as well.  He admitted (I believe this was actually caught by my conspicuously mounted GoPro) that he never even turned his head to check his blind spot.This is not the first incident I've seen here, but this is by far the most dangerous one I've seen yet.If motorists cannot be bothered to act in a safe and predictable manner then the infrastructure should be adjusted to prevent their negligent actions from harming others.  I realize removing this right turn kind of sucks, but serious injury or death because someone can't be bothered to follow the law sucks more.At a minimum, please consider a trial closing of the slip lane to see how traffic is affected for several days.

There was a black car just parked in the bike lane here today, under the "No Stopping Anytime" sign.  I have a car horn on my bike, when I honked at him he flipped me off.  I stopped at the light (Broadway @ Galileo Galilei Way) and he pulled up, rolled down his window, said something along the lines of "You're a @#$%, nigger", and then proceeded to blow through the red light and almost hit about 5 more cyclists.Please, what will it take to make this short stretch of bike lane a protected bike lane?  There is very little right turn traffic here, it'd be very simple to take most of the right turn lane and turn it into a significantly safer protected cycle track.  For bonus points, the entire block could be re-painted to allow for some of the space to be reserved for a protected bike lane in the opposite direction as well.Obviously a full fix like I've outlined above is costly and impossible to do during the winter months, but it's trivial to throw some cones down and see what happens.  We could even do this today, assuming you have some spare cones.  I'm certain it will be safer, but unfortunately only the City has the authority to make this happen.Please, share your plans for this stretch of road, let us know what your timelines are to make this better, and by all means, let us know if there is anything we can do to help!

issue_description: Cars heading westward on Cambridge St turning right into Sixth St often block the bike lane by forming a right turn lane in the bike lane and bus stop in front of 501 Cambridge. Tried biking through Porter Square this morning and taking the "Bike Left Turn Jughandle".  I like the green paint, it's far more visible.  Unfortunately, it's 100% ineffective because traffic blocks the bike lane whenever the light is green for cyclists.This morning while I'm waiting at the light a 77 bus pulled up, behind another bus, with the rear passenger door opening up right in front of my front wheel.  A bus rider gets off and starts admonishing me for "blocking her way".  I'm riding a 100lbs cargo bike, it's not something that's easily moved, and even if it were, I'm not going to move out of the way from where I'm supposed to be waiting, the bus driver shouldn't have stopped here if they couldn't clear the intersection.  While all the passengers filter off the bus the bike signal turns green, yellow, and red.  Now I'm stuck waiting for an entire extra cycle, which at this intersection is several minutes long, which kind of sucks on a cold, below freezing morning, particularly when I'm trying to do everything correctly.The premise here is sound, give cyclists a safe way to make a left turn onto Somerville Ave.  I love the basic implementation, but it's not helpful if traffic just blocks your way.  Please consider retiming the lights and reaching out to the MBTA (the most frequent offender) to train their bus drivers *not* to block the crosswalk/bike lane here.
address: Mass Ave @ Somerville Ave Cambridge, Massachusetts

issue_description: Another bike lane obstruction in the same place as last time, right in front of the Draper Lab loading dock.  Also, for the record, it appears that the loading dock did have space for the truck to park safely off the street.I called CPD, where a dispatcher quite rudely said "This is T&P's problem" and forwarded me to a very long phone menu tree.  When I finally got through to an operator at T&P they were quite polite, and happy to send an agent to ticket, but had no idea of how to record this as yet another data point, so here I am doing that right now.  Please, Obstructed Bike Lanes should be treated as a priority (but obviously not emergency) dispatch.  I shouldn't have to listen to a long phone tree to report it, that wastes valuable  minutes to get an officer to the scene to attempt to educate the vehicle's operator.Finally, yet again, I'm going to request that you do something, anything really, at this location to prevent trucks from obstructing the bike lane.  Again, I'd love to see a simple experiment done with a few skinny, tall, orange traffic cones lining the bike lane.  It's cheap, easy, and not permanent if it doesn't work.  I see no reason why we can't try this out for a few days (unless it's heavy snow, of course!).Also, can we get an official "Who to call?" number, preferably just one number 24/7, so I don't need to remember if a particular office is open or not.  CPD's non-emergency dispatch seems like the proper place for that, but probably not if the dispatchers are going to be rude to callers.

For tonight's commute home we now have a black car blocking the bike lane directly opposite where this morning's truck was.  Again, he's in a pretty clear No Stopping Zone.  I pulled up and asked if he was going to move or if I need to call the cops, he said go ahead and call the cops.  I pulled my bike onto the sidewalk and he rolls down the other window and goes, "You know what, I'll just drive around and come back and wait while you're not here."Mission accomplished?  I guess?Seriously though, when will this bike lane be made a protected bike lane?  We cannot afford to have cyclists forced to move all over the road, it's just not safe.Also, please follow up with whoever owns MA Registration COMM69 and please make sure they are aware that it is illegal (and incredibly dangerous!) to obstruct the bike lane.

Another day, another truck parked in the bike lane forcing cyclists to do crazy unsafe things just to avoid being crushed to death.  Let's tick off the problems here.  Again.1) Truck is blocking the bike lane & the majority of the right turn lane.2) Truck is stopped in a clearly marked "No Stopping Zone".3) There's a perfectly adequate loading zone THAT THE TRUCK IS BLOCKING BECAUSE IT'S STOPPED IN THE MIDDLE OF THE ROAD!Seriously, what is going on here?  Has *ANYONE* talked to Draper Labs about fixing this nonsense?  Has anyone called any of the truck companies up to try and educate?  Has anyone ever considered putting up some bollards to PREVENT trucks from doing this in the first place?  Has a truck ever even been ticketed here for blocking the bike lane?This isn't rocket science guys, though I suppose since it's literally a matter of life and death it's not far off?  If Cambridge is truly committed to Vision Zero this kind of stuff would be trivial to fix.  Do a pilot study with plain old orange traffic cones, I'm sure you have those lying around, and it'd be practically free to pilot and it could be done today if you really cared!Stop giving out excuses on why this can't be fixed.  Do something.  Start ticketing.  Start running pilot protected bike lanes.  Start educating local businesses so they can educate their suppliers.  Literally do anything other than nothing.We've had enough cyclists killed because Cambridge is stuck in a quagmire of inaction.  Break the cycle, not the cyclists.

Not only is this traffic warning sign about "bike safety" a victim-blaming response that disrespects the death of a cyclist in a dangerous intersection under the wheels of an unlicensed 18 wheeler (dangerous, huge, and unlicensed in an urban, residential area) -- it is also IN the bike lane. This is unacceptable. A sign, moved out of the space for bicycles to safely travel, could read "TRUCKS BE SAFE: LOOK FOR BIKES" or simply "LOOK FOR BIKES AND PEDESTRIANS." This is right in front of a school where many of the children bike with their parents every morning. It also is causing bikes to come up onto the sidewalk to avoid this very sign, and poses a threat to the children coming and going to take care of the plants in front of the school. Please remove this, and consider something that pays some respect to the life lost for no good reason.

A truck, MA N96958 (Commercial) was completely obstructing the bike lane (and the adjacent bus stop) here this morning.  No driver in sight when I arrived, so I called CPD.  While on the phone the driver showed up and I let him know that this was dangerous and illegal.  He blew me off and began unloading his truck.  After hanging up with CPD I let the driver know that CPD has been notified, and he told me to go "@#$% off."  Kind words friend.What's the City's plan to address these issues?  Even on a cold, raw, rainy day at least 15 cyclists passed in the 2 or 3 minutes I was stopped, this is an extremely busy commuter bicyclist route, we really need to take steps to make sure trucks are not blocking the bike lane because it's the easiest thing to do.
